				RE: Why can't I have a good theif?
			</span></a></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class="BoardRowB" colspan=3>
				Who said thieves/rogues are evil? <br>  <br> The word &quot;rogue&quot; has in the past been used to describe a dashing, carefree swashbuckler type with little regard for the law.  This is normally the same person that saves the day in the book/movie/TV show/delusional hallucination.. what's evil about that? <br>  <br> I consider EQ's rogues to be more thieves themselves than actual rogues.  However, I'm sure Verant had no desire to make a class for every single type of thiever out there, and so they bundled them up into one. <br>  <br> So you have this rogue.  Why do you assume that they are evil?  Because they skulk around in the shadows, wear black armor, have no care for laws, and stab people in the back?  That's not being evil, that's survival in their minds.  In D&amp;D, good-natured rogues are considered Chaotic Good most often. <br>  <br> In the Hobbit, Bilbo was a reluctant burglar.. heck, he didn't even know he had it in him.  I understand where you may look at EQ and say &quot;Hey, these guys are evil compared to Bilbo&quot; but I quite disagree. <br>  <br> Take a quick look at the gods these folk can worship.. often times the god isn't evil in the slightest.  There's another tip-off. <br>  <br> Enough rambling; let me get down to the suggestions on how to roleplay an EQ Rogue. <br>  <br> Sit down and think to yourself.. what caused your particular character to turn to a life of burglary?  Was he an orphan forced to live off the streets?  Come up with your own quick story as to why he is what he is.. it will help your character develop in the long run. <br>  <br> Thieves/rogues aren't evil by nature; they simply don't follow laws.  They feel that they are perfectly justified in cutting a person's purse if they leave it out dangling for all to see.  Stabbing someone in the back?  That's not a gesture of cruelty, it's one of survival.  Best to kill it before it kills you.  Hiding in the shadows and sneaking around?  Survival, again.  Bilbo did the same, after all, when sneaking past the spiders, the elves, and ol' Smaug.  You're not going to run around like a chicken with your head cut off and hop they don't chase you when it's easier not to be seen at all. <br>  <br> The way I see the different rogues out there being played: <br>  <br> Barbarian -- Gruff and silent, but good at getting what needs to be done, done. <br>  <br> Dark Elf -- This is your stereotypical evil rogue.  More an assassin, really. <br>  <br> Dwarf -- I see these being played in two main ways.. one is a gruff and grumbling type, the other is a loud, boisterous fellow that you would never suspect was the one who just picked your pocket clean. <br>  <br> Gnome -- Very quick, furtive little guys, are gnomes.. I imagine they'd be pretty quiet and just smile at you until you turn your back on them. ;) <br>  <br> Half-Elf -- I see these guys as the swashbuckling type, laughing as they leap into the fray, living as dangerously as they can. <br>  <br> Halfling -- These guys are *born* to thievery.  Still, you can play them as timid or as if they think snatching one's purse is the most natural thing in the world, like breathing. <br>  <br> Human -- Again, I see them as swashbuckling types.. <br>  <br> Wood Elf -- A silent, solemn sort, out doing what he/she is gifted to do. <br>  <br> Again, these are just suggestions... but you most certainly don't *have* to play a rogue as evil, and I hope I've shown that. :)
						<p><span class="SignatureTitle">-----signature-----</span>
